explanation:
SHA1CircularShift: The target calls this helper; include its definition to ensure it has no hidden use of memcmp or string operations that could create a MISRA violation.  
struct SHA1Context: The target reads/writes context->message_block and other members — the exact type and layout (e.g. whether message_block is a byte array and how it is filled/terminated) are needed to determine whether any memcmp would be comparing null-terminated strings.  
SHA1PadMessage: Direct caller of SHA1ProcessMessageBlock; its body must be inspected for any memcmp usage or preparation of data that could lead to memcmp comparing null-terminated strings.  
SHA1Input: Direct caller of SHA1ProcessMessageBlock; it likely populates message_block from inputs (possibly C-strings). Its implementation is required to see whether string data (null-terminated) is placed into message_block or whether memcmp is used on such strings.  
SHA1Result: Calls SHA1PadMessage; include to follow call chain and find any memcmp usage higher up that might operate on null-terminated strings related to the SHA1 processing.  
ws_get_accept_value: Calls SHA1Input (per call graph); include because it is a potential source of C-strings passed into the SHA1 functions and may reveal whether null-terminated strings flow into memcmp calls.  
memcmp: The standard library function whose usage is forbidden by the MISRA rule in the context of null-terminated strings — include to locate all uses and check their argument origins and whether they are null-terminated strings.
